        "username": "czephyr",
        "avatar_template": "https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/c/d78d45/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-04-22T09:21:14.135Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I\u2019m migrating some machines which participate to an FDB cluster.<br>\nI will phase out the old 5 machines which host the coordinators and I will be required to change the coordinator roles to process running on the new machines.</p>\n<p>Is it better to do the coordinator change in a single step or gradually?</p>\n<p>The gradual way would be to do 2 change steps by changing the coordinator list to 3 old + 2 new machines, and then on a second step switch out the 3 remaining old ones to 3 new ones having all 5 be new ones at that point.</p>\n<p>Or in a single step by just telling the cluster the new 5 coordinators are on 5 new nodes in one operation?</p>\n<p>EDIT: A further question, when then I will be excluding old nodes from the cluster, is there any downside to excluding half of the nodes in the cluster in one step? In my mind running a single exclude command will make it so the recalculation of the data topology is as optimal as possible.<br>\nCompared to running excludes node by node waiting for the cluster to fully heal.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2025-04-22T10:08:20.356Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
        "reply_to_post_number": null,
        "quote_count": 0,
